Fundamental Properties of Stars

R = radius of the star in solar units;
M = mass of the star in solar units;
T = temperature in solar units;
V = lifetime in solar lifetimes;
L = luminosity of the star in solar units

Start with temperature from type and designation

** ALL IN SOLAR EQUIVALANTS **
Mass equations
More Accurate
  M = 3 * sqrt(L)
  M = 0.9 * sqrt(R)
  M = V^-0.4
  M = 0.505 * sqrt(T)
Less Accurate
  L < 0.144 Lsol
    M = 2.3 * sqrt(L)
    M = R^0.87 * T^1.739
  L < 16 Lsol
    M = 4 * sqrt(L)
    M = T * sqrt(R)
  L < 53665.63 Lsol
    M = 3.5 * sqrt(L / 1.5)
    M = R^0.571 * T^1.143 / 1.123
  L > 53665.63 Lsol
    M = sqrt(L / 3200)
    M = sqrt(R^2 * T^2 / 3200)

Radius Equations
More Accurate
  R = M^0.9
  R = L^0.3
  R = T^1.8
  R = V^-0.36
  R = sqrt(L) / T^2

Temperature Equations
More Accurate
  T = M^0.505
  T = 1.8 * sqrt(R)
  T = 6 * sqrt(L)
  T = -5 * sqrt(V)
  4 * sqrt(L/R^2)

Lifetime Equations
Total Lifetime
  V = M^-2.5
  V = -0.36 * sqrt(R)
  V = T^-5
  V = -1.2 * sqrt(L)
Main Sequence Lifetime
  Q = 0.925 * M^-2.5
  Q = 0.925 * V

Luminosity Equations
More Accurate
  L = R^2 * T^4
Less Accurate
  M < 0.43 Msol
    L = M^2.3
  M < 2 Msol
    L = M^4
  M < 20 Msol
    L = 1.5 * M^3.5
  M > 20 Msol
    L = 3200 * M

Temperature Ranges for Spectral Types
Type - Min - Max - constant
O - 30000 - 60000 - 0.0003300
B - 10000 - 30000 - 0.0004995
A - 7500 - 10000 - 0.0039960
F - 6000 - 7500 - 0.0066600
G - 5000 - 6000 - 0.0124875
K - 3500 - 5000 - 0.0045409
M - 2400 - 3500 - 0.0166511

Numerical Spectral component from temperature(K)
  Sc = (M -T) * K
  Sc = Numeric designation for the star
  M = Max temp in Kelvin
  T = The stars temp in Kelvin
  K = a constant value associated with each spectral typeâ€‹

Temperature(K) from numerical spectral designation
  T = M - (Sc / K)